<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900502-0015</DOCNO><DOCID>900502-0015.</DOCID><HL>   What's News --   Business and Finance</HL><DATE>05/02/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1</SO><LP>   MANUFACTURING GREW in April for the first time in 11months, purchasing managers said. But construction spendingfell 1.4% in March, the first decline this year. Bothmanufacturing and construction have been hurt by the Fed'sefforts to battle inflation with high rates.                                                                                                       </LP><TEXT>   Stocks edged higher in reaction to the purchasingmanagers' report, while bond prices weakened. The Dow Jonesindustrials closed up 12.16, at 2668.92. The dollar driftedlower.   ---   Chrysler posted a $71 million profit for the firstquarter, surpassing expectations and pushing its stock up 75cents, to $15.25. Though earnings were down 80% from a yearearlier, the auto maker was expected to only break even dueto sharply lower production and slumping sales.   ---   Coca-Cola scored a major coup against Pepsi-Cola byswiping its biggest fountain client, Burger King. Cokealready supplies the nation's largest fast-food chain,McDonald's.   ---   The House approved a $1.24 trillion spending plan forfiscal 1991 that Democrats viewed as little more than theiropening position for talks with the Senate and White House.   ---   Mitsubishi Motors agreed to buy a majority stake in ValueRent-a-Car, becoming the first Japanese maker to align itselfwith a U.S. car-rental firm. Terms weren't disclosed.   ---   American General is likely to remain under pressure tofind a buyer or take other action to boost its stock pricewhether or not hostile suitor Torchmark wins today's proxyvote. The vote is expected to be close.   ---   Georgia-Pacific said it is considering selling some assetsto help pay off debt from its recent $3.74 billionacquisition of Great Northern Nekoosa.   ---   Michael Milken will be subpoenaed by a House panel, whichagreed to offer immunity to the former junk-bond king inreturn for his testimony. A hearing could be held thissummer.   ---   Carl Icahn isn't expected to win his proxy battle to splitUSX into separate steel and energy businesses. But he isforcing the company's management to consider some boldinitiatives.   ---   The Sandamp;L bailout's rising cost is causing concern at theWhite House, which said it is starting to seek a new FDICchief to handle the problem.   ---   OPEC ministers arrived in Geneva for today's start of anemergency meeting, apparently convinced that short-termproduction cuts are the only way to calm the oil markets.                                                                                                          Gasoline prices aren't expected to decline anytime soondespite the recent 20% slide in crude-oil prices.   ---   The American Stock Exchange is seeking SEC permission tolist U.S. stock-index warrants that would let investors beton the market's direction over the next three years.   ---   The New York state sales tax may soon be broadly expandedto cover such services as custom computer programming,management consulting and public relations.   ---   Group of Seven officials plan to meet in Washington Sundayto resolve issues that are holding up a proposed capitalincrease for the IMF.   ---   Legislation to stiffen penalties for workplace-safetyviolations was endorsed by the Bush administration.   ---   Markets --   Stocks: Volume 149,020,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials2668.92, up 12.16; transportation 1136.91, up 6.93; utilities204.10, up 1.01.   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3221.59, off9.21.   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 133.49, up 0.57; spotindex 134.15, up 0.42.   Dollar: 158.83 yen, off 0.07; 1.6808 marks, up 0.0012.</TEXT></DOC>